Text: Shelter[edit | edit source].

No.2307
Connections: 
Text: Main Article:Shelter.

No.2308
Connections: 
Text: Shelter is something you might consider during your first night because you won't want to be killed.

No.2309
Connections: 
Text: You can make a small hole to hide in or a small two by three house made out of wood and dirt.

No.2310
Connections: 
Text: Place torches in your preferred shelter because in light level 7 or below zombies might spawn.

No.2311
Connections: 
Text: Don't forget to build a bed to sleep until dawn (That is if you can build a bed otherwise you're gonna have to wait til dawn).

No.2312
Connections: 
Text: If you do see a cave it could be a temporary home but remember to place torches—creepers don't really make good neighbors.

No.2313
Connections: 
Text: Night time[edit | edit source].

No.2314
Connections: 
Text: For night time, the primary danger will be monsters/mobs.

No.2315
Connections: 
Text: It is a good idea to stay in your lit shelter.

No.2316
Connections: 
Text: On the other hand, if you're seeking adventure you could always arm yourself with a stone sword and go beat some mobs, if you feel like it.

No.2317
Connections: 
Text: You will be able to get some materials for further crafting, not to mention a ton of experience, which can be used later on for enchanting tools.

No.2318
Connections: 
Text: One way to avoid being attacked by monsters is to put torches, glowstone, or a jack-o-lantern by your house.

No.2319
Connections: 
Text: You will learn how to make all these things later on, but just a heads up.

No.2320
Connections: torches:1|stick:15 stick:15|torches:1 
Text: The torches are easy though, you just need to craft charcoal/coal on top of a stick.

No.2321
Connections: 
Text: If you are repeatedly getting killed, one desperate response is to go into "peaceful difficulty" (see "changing the rules", below).

No.2322
Connections: 
Text: However, consider this: This being your first day, you aren't actually losing much until the deaths (at least not after what stuff you've gathered is lost), so you can just tough it out until dawn and start again.

No.2323
Connections: 
Text: Death[edit | edit source].

No.2324
Connections: 
Text: Normally in survival mode Minecraft, when you die, all items you were carrying or wearing in your inventory are scattered around your point of death while you respawn elsewhere (unless /gamerule keepInventory is on).

No.2325
Connections: 
Text: Until you sleep in a bed, you will spawn somewhere within 10 blocks of the world spawn point.

No.2326
Connections: 
Text: This includes the first time when you started the game, so you can respawn anywhere within 20 blocks of where you first entered the world.

No.2327
Connections: 
Text: The traditional advice is to build your first shelter as close as possible to the spawn point, so if you die, you can easily find it again, or even spawn in a now-protected area.

No.2328
Connections: 
Text: Even with the variation in where you'll come back, it's good to have a lit shelter nearby the spawn point.

No.2329
Connections: 
Text: However, a problem with sheltering away from spawn is that if your death site is too far from where you respawn, your items may despawn while you're trying reach them.

No.2330
Connections: 
Text: (See below for more details.

No.2331
Connections: 
Text: ).

No.2332
Connections: 
Text: Like any dropped items in Minecraft, the items you drop when you die will despawn (disappear) after 5 minutes, unless you're more than 180 blocks or so away, that is outside of chunk update radius The problem is that if you died at night, you will find yourself stranded without your weapons and armor, so you are quite likely to get killed again, or at least find your stuff guarded by monsters.

No.2333
Connections: 
Text: Meanwhile, some of the monsters can actually pick up your stuff and use it against you! And if you spawned near your death scene, that 5-minute timer can easily go by before you can actually get back to and keep your stuff.

No.2334
Connections: 
Text: However, the above only applies until you have made and used a bed in a secure shelter.

No.2335
Connections: 
Text: Once you've done that, you have a new option: If you get killed at night, you will respawn next to your bed, so you can just go back to sleep, and wake up the next morning — the items don't “expire” while you're asleep.

No.2336
Connections: 
Text: It still may be worth keeping your bed out of chunk update range from where you're endangering yourself, but at least you won't be stranded outside at night.

